pullRequest.body:
Adds Sym2.pmap and 
 Sym2.attachWith, which is direct application of pmap. 

These functions are analogous to the functions with the same name under the namespace List and Multiset.

Oh nevermind then

Can you
1. Turn this lemma around
2. Make a copy of the lemma as it currently is, but assuming `P s(a, b)` and deducing `P a`, `P b`, rather than the other way around.

This way, `rw` with the forward direction will never create side goals.
done!

```suggestion
lemma attachWith_map_subtypeVal {s : Sym2 Î±} {P : Î± â†’ Prop} (f : âˆ€ a âˆˆ s, P a) :
```
to match the naming convention

This would require a substantial reworking of this PR, but is it any easier to first define `attachWith` and then define `pmap s f` = `s.attach.map f`? This would enable you to rely on the `map` API to hopefully simplify the proofs about `pmap`.

Would that be easier? Defining `attachWith` would be just a matter of adapting the current definition of pmap so that wouldn't be hard. But given that, at least the proofs I had to write so far, are mostly just `induction'` and `rfl`, I don't know this alternate approach can make things easier. Perhaps there is a value in using function on subtype rather than data and a proof as 2 inputs?

```suggestion
      Hq a (Sym2.mk_eq_mk_iff.2 hpq â–¸ hmem : a âˆˆ Sym2.mk q)
```

```suggestion
  aesop
```
and maybe it can even swallow a few extra tactics before

```suggestion
    s(f p.1 (H p.1 <| mem_mk_left _ _), f p.2 (H p.2 <| mem_mk_right _ _))
```
